Load packages

library(tidyverse) 
library(datasauRus)

Exercise 1

The datasaurus_dozen dataframe contains 1846 rows and 3 columns. The datasaurus_dozen dataframe contains 3 variables:

  • dataset: indicates which dataset the data are from
  • x: x-values
  • y: y-valuesda

Exercise 2

Plotting the data in the dino dataset:

dino_data <- datasaurus_dozen %>%
  filter(dataset == "dino")
ggplot(data = dino_data, mapping = aes(x = x, y = y)) +
  geom_point()

Calculating the correlation between x and y in this dataset:

dino_data %>%
  summarize(r = cor(x, y))
## # A tibble: 1 × 1
##         r
##     <dbl>
## 1 -0.0645

Exercise 3

Plotting the data in the star dataset:

star_data <- datasaurus_dozen %>%
  filter(dataset == "star")
ggplot(data = star_data, mapping = aes(x = x, y = y)) +
  geom_point()

Calculating the correlation between x and y in this dataset:

star_data %>%
  summarize(r = cor(x, y))
## # A tibble: 1 × 1
##         r
##     <dbl>
## 1 -0.0630

For the dino dataset, the r value is -0.0645. For the star dataset, the r value is -0.0630.

Exercise 5

ggplot(datasaurus_dozen, aes(x = x, y = y, color = dataset))+
geom_point()+
facet_wrap(~ dataset, ncol = 3) + # facet the dataset variable, in 3 cols
theme(legend.position = "none")

datasaurus_dozen %>%
  group_by(dataset) %>%
  summarize(r = cor(x, y)) %>%
  print()
